<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-77-0168 </DOCNO><TEXT>The study of chromosome damage in rodents living on hazardous-waste sitesmay provide evidence of important biological consequences of chronicexposure to toxic chemical wastes. This study compared bone-marrow cellsof animals (Sigmodon hispidus) taken from two superfund waste-disposalsites with those from an uncontaminated site and demonstrated that bothpopulations exposed to hazardous wastes had significantly more structuraland numerical aberrations than the control population.</TEXT></DOC>